column1: #Text=This code uses [python3.x](https://www.python.org/downloads/) (version 3.6 and higher) and requires the [Gurobi](https://www.gurobi.com/) solver.
#Text=- `OBCT.py` contains the formulations of each model for solving using Gurobi9.x
#Text=- `TREE.py` creates the necessary tree information including path, child, and other information
#Text=- `SPEED_UP.py` contains the code for the callbacks used in user fractional separation procedures
#Text=- `UTILS.py` contains the code for viewing model decision variable results and generating the .csv results files among other utility functions
#Text=- `model_runs.py` contains the code necessary to create, solve, and report results in a `.csv` file of each instance called by the user
#Text=- `results_files/` folder stores the generated `.csv` files with model metrics
#Text=- `figures/` folder stores the generated `.png` files for experimental results
#Text=- `log_files/` folder stores model `.lp` files and Gurobi `.txt` log files
#Text=- `Datasets/` folder contains the datasets used for generating experimental results
#Text=  - Note: `Datasets/` should also be used as the folder where user dataset files are stored
#Text=- Ensure the latest versions of the packages in `requirements.txt` are installed
#Text=- For an instance of `OBCT` run with one of the functions in `model_runs.py` we use following arguments (not all functional call parameters apply to all functions)
#Text=    - d : `str list`, name(s) of dataset file(s)
#Text=    - h : `int list`, maximum depth(s) of trained tree(s)
#Text=    - t : `float`, gurobi model time limit in s
#Text=    - m : `str list`, list of model(s) to use
#Text=    - r : `int list`, list of random seed(s) to use
#Text=      - `rand_seed = [k,...,k]`  for repeat use of randome state `k`
#Text=    - p : `str`, objective priority parameter used in bi-objective modeling
#Text=    - e : `str list`, model extra(s), if applicable
#Text=    - l : `boolean`, log console to `.txt` file and write model to `.lp` file, both saved to the `\\log_files` folder for each model called by user
#Text=- We assume the target column is labeled `'target'`.
#Text=Change the hard code in `model_runs.py` to change the according target column

#Text=- If results output file `-f file` is `None` the `models_run.py` calls automatically generates a `.csv` results file with the parameters of the function call as the file name saved to the `\\results_files` folder
#Text=- `-e model_extras`, `-p priorities`, and `-f file` may be `None` input arguments, all others must hold a valid value
#Text=Call the `model_runs.py` `main` function within a python file as follows to generate a model ignorning our second objective,
#Text=To run from terminal do the following,

#Text=python3 import model_runs; model_runs.main -d ['soybean-small','monk3','car','iris','climate'] -h [3,4,5] -m ['MCF1','MCF2','CUT1-ALL','CUT2-FRAC-3'] -t 3600 -e ['max_features-25'] -r [13, 58, 94, None] -c None -f 'test_results.csv' -l False
#Text=Call the `biobjective` function within a python file as follows to generate a model using the heirarchical modeling capabilities of Gurobi
#Text=To run from terminal do the following,
#Text=To generate the Pareto frontier call the `main` function in `pareto_runs.py` with the below parameters:
#Text=  - d : str list, names of dataset files
#Text=  - h : int, maximum depth of trained trees
#Text=  - t : float, gurobi model time limit in s
#Text=  - m : str list, models to use
#Text=  - r : str list, random state(s) to use
#Text=A `.png` file for each dataset called by the user is generated and stored in `\\results_figures\\` folder
#Text=We assume `-f file` is located in the `\\results_files` folder

#Text=- If results output file `-f file` is `None` the `pareto` function automatically generates a `.csv` results file with the parameters of the function call as the file name saved to the `\\results_files` folder
#Text=You can generate pareto frontiers from within a python file as follows,

#Text=For understanding model functionality associated with integer and fractional separation procedures in **CUT1** and **CUT2** models, `-e model_extras` and `-c tuning` functionality please refer to the `USAGE.md` file.
#Text=`example_code.py` contains additional instances of the above and how to call `OBCT` directly without using `model_runs.py`
